03946nam a22006375i 9783110773644DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a9783110773644  a(DE-B1597)612613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL041000 2bisacsh1 aGrigoryan, Sona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeither Belief nor Unbelief :bIntentional Ambivalence in al-Maʿarrī’s Luzūm /cSona Grigoryan. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XI, 204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History and Culture of the Middle East ,x2198-0853 ;v4500tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tSome Matters of Usage -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Milieu and Life: al-Maʿarrī in Context -- tChapter 2 Luzūmīyāt -- tChapter 3 Between Belief and Unbelief—Early Treatments and Responses -- tChapter 4 Between Belief and Unbelief—Modern Readings and Receptions -- tChapter 5 Neither Belief nor Unbelief— Intentional Ambivalence -- tChapter 6 Contradictions in Luzūmīyāt -- tConclusions -- tAppendix: Verses of Luzūm in Arabic -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book re-examines the religious thought and receptions of the Syrian poet Abū l-ʿAlāʾ al-Maʿarrī (d.1057) and one of his best known works - Luzūm mā lā yalzam (The Self-Imposed Unnecessity), a collection of poems, which, although widely studied, needs a thorough re-evaluation regarding matters of (un)belief. Given the contradictory nature of al-Maʿarrī’s oeuvre and Luzūm in particular, there have been two major trends in assessing al-Maʿarrī’s religious thought in modern scholarship. One presented al-Maʿarrī as an unbeliever and a freethinker arguing that through contradictions, he practiced taqīya, i.e., dissimulation in order to avoid persecution. The other, often apologetically, presented al-Maʿarrī as a sincere Muslim. This study proposes that the notion of ambivalence is a more appropriate analytical tool to apply to the reading of Luzūm, specifically in matters of belief. This ambivalence is directly conditioned by the historical and intellectual circumstances al-Maʿarrī lived in and he intentionally left it unsolved and intense as a robust stance against claims of certainty. Going beyond reductive interpretations, the notion of ambivalence allows for an integrative paradigm in dealing with contradictions and dissonance.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022)  aIslam.  aPoetry.  aReligion.  aal-Maʿarrī.0 cEPUBz97831107738970 cprintz978311077253140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110773644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110773644/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK